{
  "Which property is measured by the Mohs Hardness Scale?": "",
  "Resistance to scratching": "",
  "Luster, particularl": "",
  "Color, particularly": "",
  "Density, particular": "",
  "The Mohs scale ranks minerals from 1 (talc, softest) to 10 (diamond, hardest) based on their ability to resist being scratched by another material.": "",
  "Why is streak more reliable than color for mineral identification?": "",
  "Color is always the same for every mineral": "",
  "Streak changes with temperature": "",
  "Surface color can vary due to impurities, but streak remains consistent": "",
  "Streak is always white": "",
  "A mineral's surface color may vary due to trace impurities or weathering, but the streak (the color of its powder on a porcelain plate) remains consistent for a given mineral species.": "",
  "What is the hardest mineral on the Mohs scale?": "",
  "Corundum": "",
  "Quartz": "",
  "Topaz": "",
  "Diamond": "",
  "Diamond is rated 10 on the Mohs Hardness Scale, making it the hardest naturally occurring mineral known, capable of scratching all other minerals.": "",
  "Which of the following is NOT a requirement for a substance to be classified as a mineral?": "",
  "Formed by living organisms": "",
  "Crystalline structure": "",
  "Inorganic": "",
  "Naturally occurring": "",
  "By definition, minerals must be naturally occurring, inorganic, solid, have a crystalline structure, and a definite chemical composition. Substances produced by living organisms are not true minerals.": "",
  "What is the most unreliable physical property for identifying minerals?": "",
  "Hardness": "",
  "Color": "",
  "Streak": "",
  "Crystal form": "",
  "Color is the most unreliable property because many different minerals share the same color, and impurities can cause the same mineral to appear in a wide range of colors.": "",
  "Quartz has a hardness of what on the Mohs scale?": "",
  "5": "",
  "7": "",
  "2": "",
  "10": "",
  "Quartz has a hardness of 7 on the Mohs scale, making it a commonly used reference mineral that can scratch glass and most steel objects.": "",
  "Diamond and graphite are both made of pure carbon but have very different properties. Why?": "",
  "They form at the same temperature and pressure": "",
  "Their carbon atoms are arranged in different crystal structures": "",
  "One is organic and one is inorganic": "",
  "They contain different elements": "",
  "Diamond has a rigid tetrahedral crystal structure formed under extreme pressure, while graphite has layered sheets of carbon, demonstrating how crystal structure determines physical properties.": "",
  "Which mineral group is the most abundant in Earth's crust?": "",
  "Silicates": "",
  "Carbonates": "",
  "Oxides": "",
  "Sulfides": "",
  "Silicate minerals make up over 90% of Earth's crust because silicon and oxygen are the two most abundant elements in the crust, forming the silicate tetrahedron building block.": "",
  "A mineral that can be scratched by a fingernail (hardness ~2.5) must have a Mohs hardness of:": "",
  "7 or higher": "",
  "Exactly 5": "",
  "Less than 2.5": "",
  "If a fingernail with a hardness of about 2.5 can scratch a mineral, that mineral must have a hardness less than 2.5 on the Mohs scale, such as talc (1) or gypsum (2).": "",
  "Magnetite is unique among common minerals because it is:": "",
  "Always blue": "",
  "Transparent": "",
  "Naturally magnetic": "",
  "The hardest mineral": "",
  "Magnetite is one of the few naturally magnetic minerals, and its strong attraction to a magnet is a distinctive identifying property that sets it apart from other iron-bearing minerals.": "",
  "What is luster?": "",
  "The way a mineral reflects light from its surface, described as metallic, glassy, earthy, or waxy": "",
  "The hardness of a mineral, particularly regarding glassy as predicted by standard models": "",
  "The weight of a mineral, particularly regarding waxy according to conventional analysis": "",
  "The color of a mineral's powder under the given assumptions": "",
  "Luster describes the quality and intensity of light reflected from a mineral's surface, with major categories including metallic (like a metal) and non-metallic (glassy, waxy, earthy, silky, etc.).": "",
  "What is cleavage in mineral identification?": "",
  "The mineral's resistance to scratching": "",
  "The color of a mineral when powdered": "",
  "The tendency of a mineral to break along smooth, flat planes of weakness in its crystal structure": "",
  "The way a mineral bends without breaking": "",
  "Cleavage is the tendency of a mineral to break along flat, even surfaces that correspond to planes of weaker bonding in the crystal structure, producing smooth faces at consistent angles.": "",
  "What is fracture?": "",
  "The irregular, rough, or curved way a mineral breaks when it does not break along cleavage planes": "",
  "Breaking along smooth, flat planes in the context of this analysis": "",
  "A type of mineral luster, particularly regarding does following conventional understanding": "",
  "The chemical formula of a mineral within the typical range of values": "",
  "Fracture describes how a mineral breaks when it does not follow cleavage planes, producing irregular surfaces such as conchoidal (curved, shell-like), splintery, or uneven breaks.": "",
  "What is specific gravity?": "",
  "The ratio of a mineral's mass to the mass of an equal volume of water": "",
  "The speed at which a mineral falls": "",
  "The force of gravity at Earth's surface": "",
  "The weight of a mineral in grams": "",
  "Specific gravity is a dimensionless ratio comparing a mineral's density to that of water, helping to identify minerals by how heavy they feel relative to their size.": "",
  "What is streak in mineral identification?": "",
  "The color of a mineral's powder when rubbed across an unglazed porcelain plate": "",
  "A line on the mineral surface caused by weathering": "",
  "The shape of a mineral crystal": "",
  "The way light bounces off a mineral": "",
  "Streak is the color of the fine powder left behind when a mineral is rubbed across an unglazed porcelain streak plate, and it is more consistent than the mineral's external color.": "",
  "What does 'crystalline structure' mean in the definition of a mineral?": "",
  "The atoms are arranged in a regular, repeating three-dimensional pattern": "",
  "The mineral is always transparent": "",
  "The mineral dissolves easily in water": "",
  "The mineral always appears as a large visible crystal": "",
  "A crystalline structure means the atoms within a mineral are arranged in an orderly, repeating three-dimensional pattern, even if individual crystals are too small to see without magnification.": "",
  "What does 'conchoidal fracture' mean?": "",
  "A smooth, curved, shell-like fracture surface, commonly seen in quartz and obsidian": "",
  "Breaking along flat cleavage planes": "",
  "Crumbling into powder when struck": "",
  "Breaking into long splinters": "",
  "Conchoidal fracture produces smooth, curved surfaces resembling the inside of a seashell, and it is characteristic of minerals like quartz and volcanic glass such as obsidian.": "",
  "What is a polymorph?": "",
  "A mineral that changes color in different lighting": "",
  "A mineral that only forms in volcanic rock": "",
  "Minerals with the same chemical composition but different crystal structures, like diamond and graphite": "",
  "A mineral made of many different elements": "",
  "Polymorphs are minerals that share the same chemical composition but have different crystal structures, resulting in very different physical properties, as seen with diamond and graphite, both pure carbon.": "",
  "What does 'silicate mineral' mean?": "",
  "A mineral built around silicon-oxygen tetrahedra as its fundamental structural unit": "",
  "A mineral found only in sand": "",
  "A mineral that contains only silicon": "",
  "A mineral that dissolves in acid": "",
  "Silicate minerals are built around the silicon-oxygen tetrahedron (SiO4), the most common structural unit in Earth's crust, making silicates the most abundant mineral group.": "",
  "What does 'hardness' mean in the context of mineral properties?": "",
  "How heavy a mineral feels": "",
  "The temperature at which a mineral melts": "",
  "How easily a mineral breaks apart": "",
  "A mineral's resistance to being scratched, measured on the Mohs scale from 1 to 10": "",
  "Hardness is a mineral's resistance to scratching or abrasion, measured on the Mohs scale where 1 is the softest (talc) and 10 is the hardest (diamond).": "",
  "A student collecting rock samples finds a golden metallic mineral in a stream bed. Her teacher suggests testing the mineral's streak and hardness before assuming it is gold. The streak is greenish-black and the hardness is 6.5. What mineral is it most likely?": "",
  "Gold (streak is gold, hardness 2.5)": "",
  "Pyrite (streak is greenish-black, hardness 6-6.5)": "",
  "Quartz (streak is white, hardness 7)": "",
  "Calcite (streak is white, hardness 3)": "",
  "Pyrite, known as 'fool's gold,' has a metallic luster and golden color like gold, but its greenish-black streak and hardness of 6 to 6.5 distinguish it from real gold, which has a gold streak and hardness of only 2.5.": "",
  "A geologist in the field needs to determine if a white mineral sample is calcite or quartz. She drips dilute hydrochloric acid on it and sees vigorous fizzing. What should she conclude?": "",
  "It is calcite, because calcite (CaCO3) reacts with acid to produce carbon dioxide bubbles": "",
  "It is quartz, because quartz reacts with acid": "",
  "It is feldspar, because feldspar always fizzes with acid": "",
  "The acid test is inconclusive for these minerals": "",
  "Calcite (calcium carbonate) reacts vigorously with dilute hydrochloric acid, producing visible carbon dioxide bubbles, while quartz (silicon dioxide) does not react with acid at all.": "",
  "A jeweler receives two clear gemstones and must determine which is diamond and which is quartz. She tries to scratch a glass plate (hardness ~5.5) with each. Both scratch the glass. She then tries to scratch one stone with the other. Stone A scratches Stone B but not vice versa. Which stone is diamond?": "",
  "Neither stone is diamond": "",
  "Stone B, because it was scratched": "",
  "Both are diamond": "",
  "Stone A, because it scratched Stone B without being scratched itself": "",
  "Diamond (hardness 10) can scratch quartz (hardness 7) but not the reverse, so Stone A, which scratched Stone B without being scratched, must be the harder diamond.": "",
  "A museum curator is organizing a mineral exhibit and notices that two specimens of the same mineral, hematite, look completely different in color: one is silver-gray and the other is reddish-brown. Why should she still classify them as the same mineral?": "",
  "They weigh the same": "",
  "Both produce a reddish-brown streak, confirming they share the same composition despite different surface colors": "",
  "They were found in the same location": "",
  "Color variations mean they are actually different minerals": "",
  "Hematite can appear in many surface colors due to crystal habit and weathering, but the streak test always produces a characteristic reddish-brown powder, confirming both specimens are hematite.": "",
  "A construction company needs to select a mineral-based material for a cutting tool. They consider talc, quartz, and corundum. Based on the Mohs Hardness Scale, which mineral would make the best cutting tool?": "",
  "Talc (hardness 1)": "",
  "All three are equally suitable": "",
  "Corundum (hardness 9)": "",
  "Quartz (hardness 7)": "",
  "Corundum, with a Mohs hardness of 9, is the hardest of the three options and would be most effective as an abrasive cutting tool because it can scratch nearly all other minerals.": "",
  "A geology student finds a mineral specimen that breaks into thin, flat sheets. Her instructor tells her this indicates the mineral has excellent cleavage in one direction. Which mineral is she most likely holding?": "",
  "Pyrite": "",
  "Mica (muscovite)": "",
  "Olivine": "",
  "Mica minerals like muscovite have perfect basal cleavage in one direction, causing them to peel apart into thin, flat, flexible sheets, a property called perfect one-directional cleavage.": "",
  "A farmer sends a soil sample to a lab and learns it is rich in halite. The farmer notices the soil tastes salty. She asks why halite is easy to identify. What combination of properties makes halite distinctive?": "",
  "Cubic crystal form, salty taste, and three directions of cleavage at 90 degrees": "",
  "Metallic luster and high hardness": "",
  "Conchoidal fracture and glassy luster": "",
  "Reddish streak and magnetic attraction": "",
  "Halite (table salt, NaCl) is uniquely identifiable by its cubic crystal habit, distinctive salty taste, and three directions of cleavage at right angles, making it one of the easiest minerals to recognize.": "",
  "A scientist studying meteorites wants to quickly check if an iron-rich rock fragment is magnetite. She holds a small magnet near it and it is strongly attracted. A colleague argues that many dark minerals look similar. Why is the magnet test useful here?": "",
  "All dark minerals are magnetic, particularly regarding check under the given assumptions": "",
  "The magnet test determines hardness, particularly regarding magnetite as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Magnetite is one of very few common minerals that are naturally magnetic, so strong attraction to a magnet helps confirm its identity": "",
  "Only meteorite minerals are attracted to magnets following the established framework": "",
  "Magnetite is one of the few common minerals with strong natural magnetism, so attraction to a magnet is a quick and reliable diagnostic test that distinguishes it from other dark, heavy minerals.": "",
  "A student observes that a clear mineral specimen breaks with smooth, curved, shell-like surfaces rather than flat planes. Her teacher explains this is conchoidal fracture. Which mineral most likely exhibits this property?": "",
  "Feldspar": "",
  "Calcite": "",
  "Halite": "",
  "Quartz characteristically displays conchoidal fracture because it lacks cleavage planes, so it breaks along curved surfaces resembling the interior of a seashell.": "",
  "A mining engineer evaluating an ore deposit finds a mineral with metallic luster, a black streak, and a hardness of 6. It is strongly attracted to a magnet. Based on these properties, which mineral has she most likely found?": "",
  "Hematite": "",
  "Magnetite": "",
  "Galena": "",
  "Magnetite has metallic luster, a black streak, a hardness around 5.5 to 6.5, and is strongly magnetic, making it the only common mineral that matches all four of these diagnostic properties.": ""
